Bananas (
Musa spp.
) are among the most affordable and nutritious fruits available for consumption round the year in India and banana farming provides a source of livelihood to millions of Indian farmers in view of the potential scope for value addition to nearly all parts of the plant. The long lifecycle of the banana crop (12–18 months) and the semi-perennial nature of cultivation in South India (with 1–3 ratoons on average) makes it an ideal host plant for several insect pests. However, only the pseudostem weevil [
Odoiporus longicollis (Olivier)
] and rhizome weevil [
Cosmopolites sordidus (Germar)
] ( Coleoptera : Dryophthoridae ), and to some extent, banana aphid [
Pentalonia nigronervosa Coquerel
] ( Hemiptera : Aphididae ), a vector of the dreaded banana bunchy top virus disease, are considered as major pests and remain the central focus of pest management practitioners.

The mealybug identities were confirmed by molecular characterization / sequencing of the 658 base pairs (bp) region of the mitochondrial gene, cytochrome c oxidase subunit I (COXI). The mealybug samples were pre-treated with chloroform for 45 minutes at room temperature to remove the waxy coating. Traces of chloroform in these samples were washed thrice with molecular biology grade water and again pre-treated with water for 5–6 hours. DNA was extracted with the DNeasy Blood and Tissue kit (Qiagen) following the manufacturer’s instructions. PCR reaction mixture consisted of 2µl of genomic DNA, 25µl of Taq 2x master mix RED (Ampliqon, 
Denmark
), 1µl each of forward (PCOF1 5′-CCTTCAACTAATCATAAAAATATYAG-3′) and reverse primers (LepR1 5′- TAAACTTCTGGATGTCCAAAAAATCA-3′), respectively (

), and 21µl of nuclease free water. PCR amplified products were purified and subjected to Sanger sequencing at Eurofins Genomics, 
India
Pvt Ltd. COX1 sequences of the mealybugs were submitted to GenBank and accession numbers obtained (see 
Table 2
).

Coccinellid larvae and pupae associated with banana mealybugs were reared to adults in the laboratory at ambient conditions (28–35°C and 65% RH) and identified. Parasitoids emerging from identified field collected mealybug samples were also collected, sorted, and identified with the help of available literature (

; 

; 

). Photographs of the mealybugs and their natural enemies were taken using Leica M205A stereo microscope fitted with a Leica DMC 4500 digital camera. Image stacks generated were processed using CombineZP software for depth.

